= Lossless and Speech Coding

#epigraph[
  There is a big difference between a recording and a performance. A recording tries to
  capture the air pressure itself. A vocoder captures the _idea_ of what was said, and
  reconstructs the air pressure from scratch.
][
  Loosely paraphrased from Manfred Schroeder, inventor of CELP, _c._ 1985
]

Here is a puzzle that will sharpen the lesson of the entire Volume III arc. Suppose you
hand an audio compressor two recordings: the first is a full orchestral symphony (rich
harmonics, dynamic drums, soaring strings). The second is a phone call recorded in a quiet
room, one person talking, nothing else. The compressor using MP3 or AAC (Chapters 47 and
48) will squeeze both dramatically, ten-to-one or better, by exploiting what the human
ear cannot hear. But now give the same files to a _lossless_ compressor, and something
strange happens: the symphony ends up about half its original size, while the phone call
ends up at less than one-tenth. Why the colossal difference?

The answer is that lossless compression can only remove statistical redundancy (patterns
that repeat in the numbers), whereas lossy perceptual coding removes _biological_ redundancy:
the sounds your ear would have ignored anyway. Music is rich, noisy, and statistically
complex, so the lossless coder cannot do much. Speech, by contrast, is generated by a
surprisingly simple mechanical process - air blown through a pipe with resonant chambers -
and that process has deep, exploitable structure. A codec that models the _source_ of speech
instead of the waveform itself can achieve extraordinary compression. That is what this
chapter is about.

We will cover two distinct families. First, the lossless audio world: FLAC, ALAC,
WavPack, and Monkey's Audio. I'll describe what they share, how they exploit short-term linear
structure in audio samples, and why 50–60 % reduction is about as good as lossless gets
for music. Second, the speech coding world: LPC-10, CELP, ACELP, AMR, and EVS. These are codecs
that discard far more than any perceptual model would ever dare, because they know exactly
what the human vocal tract can and cannot produce.

