== FLAC: the Open Standard

*FLAC* (Free Lossless Audio Codec) is the dominant lossless audio format. It was
created by *Josh Coalson* and first released on January 15, 2001. In January 2003, it was
adopted under the Xiph.Org Foundation umbrella. In December 2024, after years of work by
the IETF CELLAR working group, FLAC was formally specified as *RFC 9639*, giving it the
same rigorous standards-track status as HTTP or TLS.

The licence is intentionally permissive: the format specification and reference software
are under a BSD licence, and there are no patents to license. This matters enormously.
The entire lossless audio ecosystem could adopt FLAC without legal risk, and hardware
manufacturers (portable players, network streamers, smartphones) could implement it
freely. Today FLAC is the default lossless format for music distribution on Bandcamp,
Qobuz, and numerous archival services.

=== How FLAC Works

FLAC divides the audio into *blocks* (also called frames) of 4,096 to 65,536 samples.
Within each block it applies one of several predictor types:

- *Verbatim*: no prediction; store raw samples (used for the first few frames, or when
  prediction would not help).
- *Constant*: all samples are the same value; store just one number.
- *Fixed prediction*: one of four simple polynomial predictors (order 0–3) computed
  without any analysis, requiring no per-frame coefficient storage.
- *LPC prediction*: full least-squares LPC up to order 32, with quantized coefficients
  stored in the frame header.

FLAC chooses whichever predictor yields the smallest total cost (coefficients +
Rice-coded residuals). For most music, order-6 to order-12 LPC wins. The Rice parameter
$k$ is optimized per partition of residuals within each frame.

FLAC also stores MD5 checksums of the audio data so corruption can be detected, and it
embeds *seektable* markers so players can jump to a time offset without decoding from the
start. The container supports arbitrary metadata (cover art, lyrics, replay-gain tags).

