== WavPack: the Hybrid Codec

*WavPack* was created by *David Bryant* and first released in mid-1998, predating FLAC
by three years. As of 2025, version 5.8 is current, with multicore encoding, WebAssembly
decoding, and support for DSD (Direct Stream Digital) audio used in SACD discs.

WavPack's signature feature, found in no other lossless codec, is its *hybrid mode*. In
hybrid mode the encoder creates _two_ output files:

- A `.wv` file: a lossy-but-high-quality compressed stream at a user-specified bitrate
  (e.g. 256 kbps). This file sounds excellent and is much smaller than lossless.
- A `.wvc` "correction" file: the exact residual needed to reconstruct the original
  losslessly. This file is typically 100–200 kbps.

When only the `.wv` file is available (e.g. streamed over a slow connection), you get
lossy playback. When both are combined, you get perfect lossless reconstruction. This
This two-tier design was ahead of its time: a form of scalable coding that the broadcast
world spent years trying to engineer into more complex codecs.

#aside[
  WavPack is one of the few audio codecs to natively handle *32-bit floating-point PCM*,
  the native format of professional digital-audio-workstation (DAW) projects. While FLAC
  supports 32-bit integer, FLAC's predictor is not designed for floats and achieves poor
  compression. WavPack uses a separate floating-point coding path that preserves all
  mantissa and exponent bits losslessly.
]

== Monkey's Audio: Maximum Compression at a Cost

*Monkey's Audio*, created by *Matthew T. Ashland* and first released in 2000, chases the
highest possible compression ratio above all other goals. Its file extension is `.ape`.
At the "Insane" compression level, APE files are typically 5–8 % smaller than FLAC at
its maximum setting, a meaningful margin when storing thousands of albums.

The price is computational cost. APE's decoder is significantly more complex than FLAC's.
At high compression levels, the codec uses high-order predictors and a more expensive
entropy coder. Many embedded players (portable music players, car stereos) struggle with
the CPU load of decoding APE at maximum settings. Early iPod models refused to play APE
at all. FLAC's decoder, by contrast, was designed to run in real time on hardware from
the early 2000s.

Monkey's Audio remains popular in certain audiophile communities, particularly in China
where `.ape` files have historically circulated widely. But for most practical purposes
(hardware compatibility, streaming, long-term archival), FLAC has won.

#misconception[
  Monkey's Audio achieves much better compression than FLAC because it uses a fundamentally
  superior algorithm.
][
  The compression gap is real but modest (5–8 % at the extremes). The difference is that
  APE uses higher-order, more expensive models. FLAC's designers deliberately capped
  complexity to ensure fast real-time decoding on constrained hardware. "Better" depends
  on your goal: if decode speed matters, FLAC is better; if file size is everything and
  CPU is free, APE is better.
]

