== Speech Coding: a Different Philosophy

Everything above stays strictly lossless. Speech codecs take the opposite extreme. A
phone call over 4G (AMR-WB) might use 12.65 kbps, compared to CD audio's 1,411 kbps.
That is a compression ratio of over 100:1. No perceptual codec designed for music comes
close to this.

How? By not compressing audio at all. Instead, speech codecs compress a *model of the
vocal tract* and a description of *what was said into it*.

=== The Vocoder Idea

The *vocoder* (voice coder) is the conceptual grandparent of all speech codecs. It was
invented by *Homer Dudley* at Bell Laboratories in 1936 and publicly demonstrated at
the New York World's Fair in 1939, where it ran on physical electrical circuits and
delighted audiences by making a machine "speak."

The key insight is this: human speech is produced by a two-part process. The *source* is
either a buzzing (voiced sounds like vowels, where the vocal cords vibrate with a
measurable pitch) or broadband noise (unvoiced sounds like "s" or "f"). The *filter* is
the vocal tract (the throat, mouth, and nose), which acts as a resonating tube that
shapes the source into the characteristic sounds of vowels and consonants.

#definition("Vocoder")[
  A vocoder encodes speech by transmitting *filter parameters* (how the vocal tract is
  shaped) and *source parameters* (voiced/unvoiced, pitch frequency, loudness) separately.
  The decoder reconstructs the speech by running the source signal through a filter with
  the received parameters. The waveform at the decoder is entirely synthesized; it is not
  a recording of the original.
]

This model is powerful because the _amount_ of information in the filter and source
parameters is far smaller than the information in the waveform. A vocal-tract filter can
be described by 10–16 numbers per 20 ms frame. A pitch period (for voiced speech) is a
single number. A voiced/unvoiced flag is one bit. The resulting bitrate is staggeringly
low. The synthesized speech sounds robotic, though, because the model does not capture all
the fine detail of the original waveform.

=== LPC-10: the Government Vocoder

The first widely deployed LPC codec was *LPC-10*, standardized by the US Department of
Defense as Federal Standard 1015 (FS-1015) and NATO STANAG 4198. It runs at exactly
2,400 bits per second (about 1.7 % of the bandwidth of a telephone-quality audio stream).
The first real-time 2,400 bps LPC implementation was demonstrated at MIT Lincoln
Laboratory in 1973.

LPC-10 analyzes each 22.5 ms frame of speech. For each frame it transmits:
- LPC coefficients (order 10): describing the vocal tract filter.
- Voiced/Unvoiced (V/UV) flag: one bit.
- Pitch period (for voiced frames): integer in samples.
- Gain: overall amplitude.

At 2,400 bps, the quality is distinctly "synthetic": intelligible but clearly artificial.
Military communications accepted this because 2,400 bps could be encrypted and transmitted
over secure satellite links that full telephone audio could not use. LPC-10 remained in
use until superseded by MELP (Mixed-Excitation Linear Prediction) in 1997.

=== CELP: Code-Excited Linear Prediction

The breakthrough that made speech codecs practical for commercial telephony was
*CELP*, proposed by *Manfred R. Schroeder* and *Bishnu S. Atal* of Bell Labs in their
landmark 1985 IEEE ICASSP paper.

The problem with LPC-10 was the source model. Using only voiced/unvoiced flags and a
single pitch estimate loses too much of the richness of real speech, and the result sounds
robotic. Schroeder and Atal's insight: instead of a simplified source model, use a
*codebook* of possible excitation signals, and transmit the index of whichever entry best
explains the current residual. The codebook entry, scaled by a gain, _is_ the excitation
signal for that frame.

The name reflects this: *Code-Excited* Linear Prediction. The excitation is determined by
a codebook index (a "code"), not a simple voiced/unvoiced rule.

