== AMR: the Adaptive Multirate Codec

*AMR-NB* (Adaptive Multi-Rate Narrowband) was adopted by 3GPP in 1998 and became the
standard speech codec for GSM and UMTS (3G) mobile networks worldwide. Its defining
feature is its *multirate* design: it can switch between *eight* bitrate modes (4.75,
5.15, 5.90, 6.70, 7.40, 7.95, 10.2, 12.2 kbps) in real time, choosing the rate that
fits current radio conditions. When the channel is good, it uses 12.2 kbps for maximum
quality. When interference increases, it drops to 4.75 kbps to maintain the connection:
intelligible low-quality speech is better than dropped calls.

AMR-NB covers narrowband speech: 300–3,400 Hz, the classic telephone frequency range.

*AMR-WB* (Adaptive Multi-Rate Wideband), also known as *G.722.2*, was selected by 3GPP
in December 2000 and standardized in January 2002. It extends the audio bandwidth to
50–7,000 Hz, a substantial improvement in naturalness and speaker recognition. The
difference between narrowband and wideband is immediately audible: narrowband speech
sounds "telephone-y," while wideband sounds close to face-to-face conversation. AMR-WB
supports nine modes ranging from 6.60 to 23.85 kbps.

Both AMR-NB and AMR-WB use ACELP under the hood.

