=== Why AMR Changed the World

Before AMR, mobile phones used a single fixed codec: GSM-FR (Full Rate) at 13 kbps.
Quality was fixed regardless of channel conditions. When the signal weakened, calls
dropped rather than gracefully degrading. AMR's rate-switching was a fundamental
architectural improvement: it turned a binary "connected/disconnected" into a continuous
quality spectrum. This is the same insight that drives adaptive bitrate (ABR) streaming
in video (Chapter 55): match your bitrate to what the channel can support.

#history[
  The AMR-WB codec algorithm was developed primarily at *Nokia Research Center* (Finland)
  and *Ericsson Research* (Sweden), submitted to 3GPP as the "VOICEAGE" candidate in
  1999–2000. Its inventor, *Vilmos Varsa* (Nokia), along with Ericsson's team, won the
  3GPP selection in December 2000. AMR-WB is now also ITU-T G.722.2, the first time
  the same codec held both a 3GPP standard number and an ITU-T recommendation. This reflected
  the global unification of telephony standards in the 2000s.
]

== EVS: Enhanced Voice Services

By the mid-2010s, mobile networks were transitioning from circuit-switched voice (2G/3G)
to *VoLTE* (Voice over LTE), which carries voice as IP packets over 4G. This created both an
opportunity and a need for a better codec. EVS is the result.

*EVS* (Enhanced Voice Services) was standardized by 3GPP in December 2014 as Release 12
(TS 26.441–26.448). It is a major step beyond AMR-WB in several respects:

- *Bandwidth*: EVS supports narrowband (up to 4 kHz), wideband (up to 8 kHz), super-wideband
  (up to 14 kHz), and full-band (up to 20 kHz) audio. Full-band covers the entire audible
  range of typical speech, plus music.
- *Bitrates*: 5.9 to 128 kbps across all modes. At the low end, EVS is a speech-only codec;
  at the high end (64–128 kbps full-band), it delivers near-transparent quality for music.
- *Mixed content*: At higher bitrates EVS uses an MDCT-based coding layer for music and
  background audio, alongside ACELP for speech. It switches between them frame by frame.
- *AMR-WB compatibility*: EVS includes an AMR-WB-compatible interoperability mode so
  calls can hand off between EVS and AMR-WB networks without disruption.
- *Error concealment*: Designed for LTE packet loss, with sophisticated packet loss
  concealment algorithms.

