#exercise("50.2", 1)[
  Explain in plain words why Rice codes are near-optimal for LPC residuals.
  What statistical property of the residuals makes them a good fit?
]
#solution("50.2")[
  LPC residuals follow an approximately Laplacian (two-sided exponential) distribution:
  most values cluster near zero, with the probability of value $n$ proportional to
  $lambda^(|n|)$ for some $lambda < 1$. Rice codes are optimal for geometric distributions,
  which are the discrete analogue of the exponential. By choosing the Rice parameter $k$
  to match the typical magnitude of residuals in each block, the coder assigns short
  codes to common small values and longer codes to rare large values, matching the
  distribution and approaching the entropy limit.
]

#exercise("50.3", 2)[
  Write a Python function `rice_encode(values: list[int], k: int) -> list[int]` that
  takes a list of signed integers and returns a list of bit counts (the total bits needed
  to Rice-encode each value, using the zigzag mapping for negatives). Compute the total
  bits for `values = [0, 1, -1, 3, -5, 10]` at `k = 2` and at `k = 3`. Which k is
  better?
]
#solution("50.3")[
  ```python
  def zigzag(n: int) -> int:
      return 2 * n if n >= 0 else -2 * n - 1

  def rice_bits(values: list[int], k: int) -> int:
      total = 0
      for v in values:
          u = zigzag(v)
          q = u >> k
          total += q + 1 + k  # unary(q) + stop bit + k remainder bits
      return total

  vals = [0, 1, -1, 3, -5, 10]
  print(rice_bits(vals, 2))  # k=2: total bits
  print(rice_bits(vals, 3))  # k=3: total bits
  ```
  k=2 gives: zigzag → [0,2,1,6,9,20]; quotients $q = u >> 2$ are $[0,0,0,1,2,5]$; bits per
  value are $q+1+2$: (0+1+2)+(0+1+2)+(0+1+2)+(1+1+2)+(2+1+2)+(5+1+2) =
  3+3+3+4+5+8 = 26.
  k=3 gives: same zigzag; quotients $q = u >> 3$ are $[0,0,0,0,1,2]$; bits per value are
  $q+1+3$: (0+1+3)+(0+1+3)+(0+1+3)+(0+1+3)+(1+1+3)+(2+1+3) = 4+4+4+4+5+6 = 27.
  k=2 is better (26 < 27 bits) for this distribution of values.
]

#exercise("50.4", 2)[
  In CELP, the encoder must transmit the index into a fixed codebook of 1,024 entries
  for each subframe. Each frame (20 ms at 8 kHz = 160 samples) has 4 subframes.
  (a) How many bits per frame does just the fixed-codebook index cost?
  (b) The adaptive codebook (pitch) uses an integer lag from 20 to 143 samples;
  how many bits is that?
  (c) The LPC coefficients are quantized with 36 bits/frame. If each frame also has a gain
  parameter using 7 bits and a V/UV flag bit, what is the total bitrate at 50 frames/second?
]
#solution("50.4")[
  (a) $log_2(1024) = 10$ bits/subframe $times$ 4 subframes $= 40$ bits for fixed codebook
  indices. (b) Lag range $= 143 - 20 + 1 = 124$ values; $ceil(log_2 124) = 7$ bits.
  (c) Per frame: 36 (LPC) + 40 (fixed codebook) + 7 (adaptive codebook) + 7 (gain) +
  1 (V/UV) = 91 bits. At 50 frames/s: $91 times 50 = 4,550$ bps ≈ 4.5 kbps.
  Actual codecs add more bits for refined quantization and multiple subframe gains,
  reaching 5.9–8 kbps for narrow-band ACELP codecs.
]

#exercise("50.5", 2)[
  Compare FLAC and ALAC from a format-design perspective. Why did Apple choose to wrap
  ALAC inside an MP4 container? What is lost and what is gained by this choice?
]
#solution("50.5")[
  Apple chose MP4 because iTunes already used MP4/M4A for AAC, and sharing the container
  format means the same tools, libraries, metadata APIs, and hardware parsers work for
  both lossy (AAC) and lossless (ALAC) content. Users see one file type; hardware has
  one container parser to implement.
  Lost: slightly more container overhead; MP4 requires parsing atom structures not needed
  for FLAC's simpler bitstream; random seeking requires the "moov" atom, which can be at
  the end of a file (a streaming problem).
  Gained: rich metadata (artwork, chapters, iTunes Store metadata); single-format
  ecosystem compatibility; unified library management in Apple software.
]

#exercise("50.6", 3)[
  Design a thought experiment. A phone call lasts 30 seconds. One side uses AMR-NB at
  12.2 kbps; the other uses FLAC. Both record the same person speaking in a quiet room.
  (a) Estimate the file sizes for each (raw PCM at 8 kHz, 16-bit, 1 channel for AMR-NB;
  44.1 kHz, 16-bit, 1 channel for FLAC). (b) Compute the effective compression ratio of
  each versus their respective PCMs. (c) Why is AMR-NB's ratio so much higher? Use the
  concepts of the chapter: source model, entropy of residuals, lossless ceiling.
]
#solution("50.6")[
  (a) AMR-NB: 12.2 kbps × 30 s / 8 = 45.75 kB compressed. Raw PCM: 8,000 × 2 × 30 =
  480,000 bytes = 468 kB. FLAC: raw 44,100 × 2 × 30 = 2,646,000 bytes ≈ 2.52 MB;
  FLAC for speech typically reaches ~45 % of raw ≈ 1.13 MB.
  (b) AMR-NB ratio: 468 / 45.75 ≈ 10.2×. FLAC ratio: 2,520 / 1,130 ≈ 2.2×.
  (c) AMR-NB compresses a _model_ (10 LPC coefficients + pitch + gain + codebook index
  per 20 ms frame), not the waveform. The total information per frame is ~100 bits
  regardless of how complex the speech is. FLAC must preserve every sample's exact value;
  the entropy of the speech residuals is still high even after LPC prediction, because
  every subtle phoneme detail must survive. AMR-NB discards all waveform detail below
  the level of the ACELP model's resolution; everything the model cannot represent is
  simply dropped. That is why it achieves 10× versus FLAC's 2×: AMR-NB is compressing
  _linguistic content_, not audio samples.
]

== Further Reading

- #link("https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9639.txt")[Coalson et al. (IETF CELLAR, 2024). _Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC)_. RFC 9639.] The formal IETF specification of FLAC, published December 2024.

- #link("https://xiph.org/flac/2024/12/19/rfc-9639-published.html")[Xiph.Org Foundation. _FLAC is now formally specified in RFC 9639_. December 2024.] The official announcement with context on the years-long CELLAR working group effort.

- #link("https://speechprocessingbook.aalto.fi/Transmission/Code-excited_linear_prediction_CELP.html")[Aalto University Speech Processing Textbook. _Code-Excited Linear Prediction (CELP)_.] A rigorous, freely accessible treatment of CELP with worked examples of the analysis-by-synthesis loop.

- #link("https://www.3gpp.org/news-events/3gpp-news/evs-news")[3GPP. _Enhanced Voice Services Codec for LTE_. 2014.] The official 3GPP announcement of EVS standardization, with architecture overview.

- #link("https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.11846")[Valin, J.-M. and Skoglund, J. (2019). _LPCNet: Improving Neural Speech Synthesis Through Linear Prediction_. arXiv:1810.11846.] The paper that showed classical LPC coefficients combined with a neural decoder can beat CELP at 1.6 kbps.

- #link("https://www.aes.org/e-lib/browse.cfm?elib=8079")[Brandenburg, K. (1999). _MP3 and AAC Explained_. AES 17th International Conference.] Karlheinz Brandenburg's own account of the development of MP3 and AAC, valuable context for how the perceptual coding paradigm was established.

- #link("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WavPack")[WavPack Wikipedia article.] Covers the hybrid mode in detail and the evolution through version 5.x.

#bridge[
  We have now covered the full range of audio compression, from psychoacoustics and
  lossy perceptual codecs (Chapters 46–49) to lossless and speech coding (this chapter).
  Audio, however, is only half the story of the media pipeline that delivers most of the
  world's compressed bits. The vast majority of data flowing across the internet is _video_:
  moving images at 24–120 frames per second, each frame as complex as the JPEG images of
  Chapter 42, but with the added dimension of time. Chapter 51 introduces the idea that
  makes video compression possible at all: *motion compensation*. If two consecutive video
  frames are similar, we can describe the second frame as a slightly shifted version of the
  first, plus a small correction. The correction is far cheaper to code than a new frame.
  That is the insight behind every video codec from H.261 (1988) to AV1 (2018) to the
  learned neural video codecs of Chapter 59.
]
